I have little interest in trying to abstract the installation of debuginfo packages. Many distros do things so differently that it just ends up making more work for me.

target_title: Debuginfod support

note.body:
For those who don't use debuginfod and instead use distro debug packages (ex: with `dnf debuginfo-install` or the APT equivalent, or some immutable distros equivalent I guess), would it be easier, more difficult, or next to impossible for Sysprof to install those when debuginfod is not present?

Alternatively (and probably much more simply), a stopgap approach I could imagine would be either:
* Offering a "Copy filename to clipboard" contextual menu action when you right-click an item (in the callgraph rows or in the flamegraph cells)?
* …or show some headerbar info button (if not action infobar) that tells you that it's missing debug symbols, then clicking the button would show the list of those files in a scrollable view that you can copy from?

That way, users could selectively copy & paste filenames to be used for their terminal command to install everything (or some of it; there are cases where I forego some overly huge debuginfo packages) at once using the system packages, for example as arguments to the `dnf debuginfo-install` command, since it can figure out package names from individual files like that (right now I have to manually type the whole path and exact filename into the command, and it's somewhat tedious and typo-prone).

I'm thinking that the "list of files without debug symbols" dialog approach might have the educational advantage of letting newbie testers know that their capture is incomplete, with a bird's eye view, making it easier to solve… which might help raise the quality of sysprof captures being attached to bug reports out there in general. I realize the dialog-style idea would probably fall into the "needs design" category, but I'm at least floating the idea out here to see if it could be technically/architecturally acceptable to begin with.

target_title: Fails to resolve most symbols on Silverblue (target in toolbox, or flatpak, or with CLI on the host)

note.body:
Translating paths through the mount namespaces on Silverblue is extremely difficult.

The first thing to look at would be what the mount namespace looks like inside the apps. Also check to see that we picked up the `maps` file for the process in question. This stuff is in the "Files" section.

Both `overlay` and `btrfs` complicate things more, especially if we need to translate subvolumes.

What I do for this stuff, is generally add `g_print()` all over `sysprof_mount_namespace_translate()` to see what is going on.
